snippet: Pro-democracy protests that swept onto the streets of Hong Kong 11 weeks ago faced a muted ending on Monday, when the police prepared to dismantle the last remaining road occupation.
abstract: Pro-democracy protests in Hong Kong come to a muted ending following three months of tumult, as police dismantle last remaining road occupation; High Court holds brief hearing for student activist Joshua Wong and about 30 other arrested protesters, adjourning case until early next year; demonstrators express sense of achievement, despite fact that government gave no substantial concessions.

byline.contributor: Alan Wong and Hilda Wang contributed reporting.

lead_paragraph: Pro-democracy protests that swept onto the streets of Hong Kong 11 weeks ago faced a muted ending on Monday, when the police prepared to dismantle the last remaining road occupation.

headline.main: Three Months of Protests End Quietly in Hong Kong
headline.print_headline: Three Months of Protests End Quietly in Hong Kong
